1
00:00:00,875 --> 00:00:12,929
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-harto sambha sambodasa Hommies to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Awakened One.

2
00:00:14,891 --> 00:00:19,577
Yeah, so some of you who read my tip, I don't know many people read the stuff.

3
00:00:19,597 --> 00:00:20,559
Some of you did read it.

4
00:00:21,320 --> 00:00:29,109
You'll know the basic content, but I thought I would speak to that particular tip that I did on joy, sympathetic joy.

5
00:00:29,932 --> 00:00:40,896
And I just don't remember any instructions by my teachers to develop joy or compassion for that matter, or even equanimity.

6
00:00:41,819 --> 00:00:45,447
None of the Burmese Sayadaws taught me that at all.

7
00:00:45,707 --> 00:00:46,789
It was always about metta.

8
00:00:47,210 --> 00:00:50,237
Now, of course, there is a there's a certain.

9
00:00:50,572 --> 00:01:17,170
reason for that maybe because once we've established metta it's obviously easier for us to respond to other people's suffering and their joy and to be equanimous within ourselves even though we are surrounded by suffering and the joy doesn't move out into sort of excitement or indulgence

10
00:01:17,537 --> 00:01:19,379
So the meta really is the base.

11
00:01:20,120 --> 00:01:25,284
Once that's established, we can presume the other illimitables will arise.

12
00:01:25,566 --> 00:01:30,870
So what we mean by illimitable is, of course, that these qualities can be developed indefinitely.

13
00:01:30,891 --> 00:01:32,231
You know, it's just up to us.

14
00:01:32,272 --> 00:01:36,615
You can go up to the highest absorption, if you wish, with them.

15
00:01:37,637 --> 00:01:41,421
And it's also known as the Brahma Vihara.

16
00:01:41,480 --> 00:01:46,566
So just to remind you, Brahma was the chief god of the Vedic system.

17
00:01:46,984 --> 00:01:52,492
And so what he's saying is that this is the most beautiful heart state that we can experience.

18
00:01:52,992 --> 00:01:54,293
It's one of the most beautiful.

19
00:01:55,314 --> 00:01:58,998
Actually, you can develop any virtue illimitably.

20
00:01:59,480 --> 00:02:03,465
It's just that these are the four, what we can call them, social virtues.

21
00:02:03,864 --> 00:02:10,612
And it's important for us to balance, you know, the compassion.

22
00:02:13,764 --> 00:02:19,853
Especially now when, you know, we can see that the world is sort of beginning to crash.

23
00:02:20,473 --> 00:02:26,622
We can have terrible forebodings of what's going to happen economically, politically, et cetera, et cetera.

24
00:02:27,282 --> 00:02:30,366
So somehow you have to be careful if you are listening to the news.

25
00:02:31,568 --> 00:02:33,911
I know some people just don't listen to the news anymore.

26
00:02:33,931 --> 00:02:35,973
It's just too depressing, too upsetting.

27
00:02:36,514 --> 00:02:41,781
But if you are, you have to sort of balance it a bit with joy and happiness.

28
00:02:42,283 --> 00:02:52,734
Sometimes on retreat, which I'm going to lead a retreat soon, I'll often say, at the end of the day, we do a meditation on joy.

29
00:02:52,774 --> 00:02:58,057
And I say, bring to mind moments of the day when you felt joyful.

30
00:02:58,679 --> 00:03:01,341
And one or two people tell me afterwards that they can't remember any.

31
00:03:03,163 --> 00:03:07,026
So the reason for that, of course, is that we're not paying attention to it.

32
00:03:08,026 --> 00:03:09,709
That's understandable because

33
00:03:10,211 --> 00:03:21,310
Unless you're feeling ecstatic joy or big joy, you don't notice the little moments when you feel content, fairly content when you feel fairly happy, nothing particularly exciting, right?

34
00:03:21,330 --> 00:03:22,752
In fact, we don't want excitement.

35
00:03:23,574 --> 00:03:28,962
And so not paying attention to it means that we're not clicking on, you see.

36
00:03:29,568 --> 00:03:36,161
And when we do start paying attention to these moments of joy, then they grow because of that attention.

37
00:03:36,341 --> 00:03:40,770
So remember, an act of attention is an act of intention.

38
00:03:40,830 --> 00:03:42,252
It's an empowering act.

39
00:03:42,993 --> 00:03:47,423
Your awareness, notice, your attention notices what's happening.

40
00:03:47,443 --> 00:03:52,352
And when it's a full attention, it becomes a full, it fills up your whole consciousness.

41
00:03:52,973 --> 00:03:54,216
And in that way, it grows.

42
00:03:54,736 --> 00:04:04,657
So we have to train ourselves in periods where we're feeling sort of downcast to pay attention when any bit of joy comes up.

43
00:04:04,677 --> 00:04:05,699
Ah, there's a bit of joy.

44
00:04:05,740 --> 00:04:06,983
Fancy that, you see.

45
00:04:10,304 --> 00:04:13,747
And of course, we have to make the distinction between joy and excitement.

46
00:04:13,788 --> 00:04:26,283
So excitement is that bit of indulgence where we become attached to a certain joy, which is understandable, but it unfortunately causes consequences, which is an obvious one is grief at loss.

47
00:04:26,603 --> 00:04:27,545
Yeah.

48
00:04:27,564 --> 00:04:29,586
The fear of loss, the anxiety of loss.

49
00:04:30,067 --> 00:04:32,310
But joy is very cool.

50
00:04:32,391 --> 00:04:33,612
It doesn't have that, you see.

51
00:04:34,064 --> 00:04:38,369
It's the difference on your Christmas cake between marzipan and icing.

52
00:04:38,709 --> 00:04:39,889
See, the icing's too much.

53
00:04:39,930 --> 00:04:40,870
You should always take it off.

54
00:04:41,072 --> 00:04:42,612
It's very bad for you, right?

55
00:04:42,653 --> 00:04:46,918
But the marzipan's fantastic, even though it's only got a bit of sugar.

56
00:04:47,038 --> 00:04:49,521
Well, compared to icing, see?

57
00:04:49,540 --> 00:04:50,581
So that's your distinction.

58
00:04:57,728 --> 00:04:59,050
So joy is quiet.

59
00:04:59,151 --> 00:05:00,072
It's pleasant.

60
00:05:00,305 --> 00:05:03,767
At times, very pleasant mental state, even to the point of absorption.

61
00:05:04,108 --> 00:05:06,451
It's always accompanied with calmness.

62
00:05:06,571 --> 00:05:07,211
This is the point.

63
00:05:07,252 --> 00:05:08,052
Always calm.

64
00:05:08,413 --> 00:05:10,254
There's always a sense of equanimity there.

65
00:05:10,675 --> 00:05:13,096
It doesn't demand that you keep it going.

66
00:05:13,197 --> 00:05:14,519
When it goes, it just goes.

67
00:05:14,858 --> 00:05:16,540
And that's fine.

68
00:05:17,440 --> 00:05:22,206
And it's always appropriate to the joyful situation you're in.

69
00:05:23,067 --> 00:05:26,110
You know, we can feel joy for ourselves when we've succeeded something.

70
00:05:26,209 --> 00:05:26,910
So that's fine.

71
00:05:26,990 --> 00:05:28,692
You know, there's nothing wrong with that.

72
00:05:29,127 --> 00:05:35,257
And when we're with somebody who is joyful, you know, we respond with that joy.

73
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:37,141
And it's appropriate.

74
00:05:37,442 --> 00:05:39,786
It's sort of to the situation.

75
00:05:41,168 --> 00:05:48,622
You've only got to think of, you know, parents when they rejoice in their children, children's successes.

76
00:05:48,742 --> 00:05:52,350
It's very, you know, it's sort of natural to do so.

77
00:05:54,742 --> 00:06:09,978
And one of the reasons that we're not really aware of the little joys that pass through us during the day, the little happinesses, the little contentments, is that, of course, we're much more aware of the horrible things that might happen, perceived dangers.

78
00:06:09,997 --> 00:06:13,262
I suppose it's all got to do with our evolution.

79
00:06:13,281 --> 00:06:14,543
That's what they say anyway.

80
00:06:14,963 --> 00:06:22,271
But the fact is that unless we pay attention to these little joys, they won't grow.

81
00:06:22,290 --> 00:06:23,331
Simple as that.

82
00:06:23,672 --> 00:06:24,413
They won't grow.

83
00:06:25,675 --> 00:06:31,000
I like to quote the mystical romantic poet William Blake on this.

84
00:06:31,019 --> 00:06:32,701
He always has a lovely verse.

85
00:06:32,721 --> 00:06:35,382
He who binds himself to a joy, I'm sure you know it.

86
00:06:35,704 --> 00:06:40,728
He who binds himself to a joy does the winged life destroy.

87
00:06:41,408 --> 00:06:47,012
But he who kisses a joy as it flies lives in eternity's sunrise.

88
00:06:48,093 --> 00:06:51,377
So eternity here can be understood as the ever present moment.

89
00:06:53,057 --> 00:06:54,939
It's not a matter of time as such.

90
00:06:58,598 --> 00:07:07,274
It also has the positive effect of undermining envy and jealousy.

91
00:07:07,954 --> 00:07:14,047
I personally always thought of envy as something that, you know, when you want what somebody else has.

92
00:07:15,168 --> 00:07:18,415
Sometimes it can even be a compliment if you actually don't want it.

93
00:07:18,814 --> 00:07:22,362
So if you say, well, I envy your new car.

94
00:07:23,894 --> 00:07:27,360
and there's no desire for that car in you, that's fine.

95
00:07:27,781 --> 00:07:29,466
That's one way we use it.

96
00:07:29,485 --> 00:07:32,151
But envy normally is wanting what the other person has.

97
00:07:32,591 --> 00:07:37,502
And jealousy, wanting what they have and also hating them for having what they have.

98
00:07:38,064 --> 00:07:39,387
So there's a bit of hatred in there.

99
00:07:40,048 --> 00:07:42,814
But it's also, I think, it involves...

100
00:07:43,401 --> 00:07:50,632
It comes sometimes a loss of fear of losing what you have to a rival.

101
00:07:51,333 --> 00:07:54,137
I mean, in a relationship that can happen.

102
00:07:54,737 --> 00:07:57,401
So jealousy comes up.

103
00:07:58,884 --> 00:08:02,889
So as it says in the actual discourses, there's a lovely line.

104
00:08:02,908 --> 00:08:06,894
Envy is abandoned by one who develops sympathetic joy.

105
00:08:10,029 --> 00:08:17,040
So that's something to really work on if we find ourselves being envious and jealous.

106
00:08:19,122 --> 00:08:23,769
And it has the effect then therefore of lessening any resentment or selfishness.

107
00:08:29,916 --> 00:08:34,062
It undermines that sort of rivalry, especially at work.

108
00:08:34,432 --> 00:09:02,768
where you have colleagues or work work people whom you see are doing better than you etc you know it can get you can get pretty nasty i had an occasion with that myself actually um i was i was offered a promotion and the funny thing was that it wasn't really a promotion to do with my department that i was in so i was in the uh what was it called um

109
00:09:04,232 --> 00:09:07,836
general education department in an FE college.

110
00:09:07,857 --> 00:09:18,811
And what had happened was after the great and honorable Mrs. Thatcher brought in her new rules, there was a huge amount of unemployment in Birmingham.

111
00:09:18,971 --> 00:09:25,919
It rose from 16, I remember this, it rose from six to 16% in six months.

112
00:09:26,591 --> 00:09:33,297
And I had the idea that as an FE college with all our trainings, we could get some of them in, you see.

113
00:09:33,658 --> 00:09:36,349
So I started this program for them.

114
00:09:36,750 --> 00:09:42,477
Now, of course, the people who wanted the promotion were the engineers, were the electricians.

115
00:09:42,839 --> 00:09:47,124
They didn't expect me teaching, you know, sociology or something.

116
00:09:47,443 --> 00:09:53,211
At the time, I was teaching English to immigrants.

117
00:09:53,231 --> 00:09:56,495
So there was this sort of real rivalry there.

118
00:09:56,515 --> 00:09:57,277
It was quite horrible.

119
00:09:57,716 --> 00:09:59,980
And one man took great deception to me, you know.

120
00:10:00,740 --> 00:10:02,383
Anyway, I left and became a monk.

121
00:10:02,403 --> 00:10:03,804
So they were all right in the end.

122
00:10:09,150 --> 00:10:18,639
For those of you, of course, oh, yeah, there's an important point here, which is about the body and mind.

123
00:10:18,659 --> 00:10:21,783
So in Buddhism, the body and mind are two different energies.

124
00:10:22,364 --> 00:10:23,183
They're not the same.

125
00:10:24,345 --> 00:10:29,289
And when you die, it's the mental body that rises out of the physical body, right?

126
00:10:32,332 --> 00:10:35,495
And what the body does is it's like a sounding board.

127
00:10:35,816 --> 00:10:37,538
It resonates the heart.

128
00:10:37,855 --> 00:10:39,758
It resonates against the body.

129
00:10:40,438 --> 00:10:55,479
And you may actually have the experience when you are in an emotion, when you're actually absorbed into an emotion and you're feeling it and you're seeing what its characteristics are.

130
00:10:55,960 --> 00:11:01,888
You may just have the experience where they actually separate and you can see that the body makes everything worse.

131
00:11:02,256 --> 00:11:08,164
And actually, whatever you're suffering from, say the depression, it's the body that feels the heaviness.

132
00:11:08,325 --> 00:11:12,409
It's the body that makes it really quite difficult to bear.

133
00:11:13,331 --> 00:11:16,855
So there is that combination, you see.

134
00:11:16,956 --> 00:11:29,110
So that means, and according to what I've read, I don't understand the chemistry or anything at all, but basically our cells have receptors for various types of hormones.

135
00:11:29,812 --> 00:11:30,373
And if

136
00:11:30,741 --> 00:11:34,506
You've got depressive hormones constantly coming into the body.

137
00:11:35,048 --> 00:11:47,384
Those receptors grow at the expense of those receptors that receive the chemicals that make you happy.

138
00:11:47,924 --> 00:11:52,650
So, you know, it's like dopamine, endorphins, all those things that make you happy.

139
00:11:52,691 --> 00:11:54,754
The receptors are less.

140
00:11:55,114 --> 00:11:59,500
Now, the thing is, I'm not so sure you'd be particularly aware of that.

141
00:12:00,120 --> 00:12:05,788
Because you would just, how can I say, when you feel depressed, you'd feel heavily depressed.

142
00:12:05,969 --> 00:12:13,698
But when you feel joy, you wouldn't know that actually you could feel more joyful if you hadn't developed depression so much.

143
00:12:15,019 --> 00:12:24,913
I know this is a very contorted way of talking about this, but I'm trying to get across that there's actually a physical reason for practicing joy, right?

144
00:12:25,349 --> 00:12:38,715
And, you know, in whatever way you can raise it, you know, walking in nature, in a park or whatever, meeting friends, anything that lifts the heart has a direct effect upon the body.

145
00:12:39,355 --> 00:12:45,889
I mean, we know that because, you know, bad mental states can actually make you physically ill. Yeah.

146
00:12:46,813 --> 00:12:49,277
But it's good to remind ourselves of that.

147
00:12:49,937 --> 00:12:50,278
Okay.

148
00:12:50,817 --> 00:12:54,822
So there's lots of reasons there for developing joy.

149
00:12:54,863 --> 00:13:02,071
And we may as well end this talk with the actual practice.

150
00:13:03,011 --> 00:13:12,822
So if we just sit quietly for a moment, and then we'll just repeat these phrases and go through the process that we do when we practice it with metta.

151
00:13:13,683 --> 00:13:14,104
Okay.

152
00:13:17,222 --> 00:13:19,765
So make sure that you're sitting, you know, comfortably.

153
00:13:19,785 --> 00:13:23,311
It doesn't have to be as if you're sitting in vipassana.

154
00:13:23,831 --> 00:13:24,893
Make sure you're comfortable.

155
00:13:24,952 --> 00:13:25,813
That's the important thing.

156
00:13:27,075 --> 00:13:33,062
And then just drawing ourselves inwardly and just recognizing the mental state we're in.

157
00:13:33,082 --> 00:13:40,631
And just resting with that for a moment.

158
00:13:57,250 --> 00:14:04,505
And then in the same way that we do with Metta, bring somebody to mind who raises joy when you see them.

159
00:14:04,525 --> 00:14:10,720
It can even be a comedian, you know, somebody who brings a sense of joy into the heart.

160
00:14:18,412 --> 00:14:20,274
And it's good to have a smile on the face.

161
00:14:20,434 --> 00:14:21,375
It's good to have a smile.

162
00:14:22,136 --> 00:14:24,801
It doesn't have to be a great big Richter smile, you know.

163
00:14:25,802 --> 00:14:30,229
But a smile does release all the endorphins or whatever.

164
00:14:33,614 --> 00:14:37,360
And just to feel that on your face, a sort of a gentle smile.

165
00:14:38,802 --> 00:14:45,751
And you're bringing somebody to mind who makes you joyful when you see them.

166
00:14:48,365 --> 00:14:50,369
And the blessings are, may you be joyful.

167
00:14:50,408 --> 00:14:53,293
May you be ever more joyful.

168
00:14:53,333 --> 00:15:00,749
And if you wish, may you enjoy the sublime happiness of Nibbana.

169
00:15:02,631 --> 00:15:03,875
So may you be joyful.

170
00:15:08,703 --> 00:15:10,407
May you be ever more joyful.

171
00:15:15,802 --> 00:15:41,607
may you experience the sublime happiness of nibbana so we can bring somebody who's helped us in our lives offer them the blessings of joy

172
00:16:02,631 --> 00:16:05,740
and that all those who are near and dear to us

173
00:16:31,217 --> 00:16:33,886
Friends, people at work, whomever we wish

174
00:17:03,432 --> 00:17:07,299
Choosing a neutral person, someone we see but don't know.

175
00:17:40,877 --> 00:17:43,969
turning that joy towards ourselves.

176
00:18:13,311 --> 00:18:16,575
We can even bring someone to mind that we're having difficulties with.

177
00:18:19,057 --> 00:18:22,000
Not big difficulties, but difficult.

178
00:18:40,180 --> 00:18:42,221
Radiating outwardly to each other.

179
00:18:43,163 --> 00:18:46,473
May we, our present spiritual companion,

180
00:19:17,555 --> 00:19:20,005
and to our neighbors and neighborhood,

181
00:19:49,211 --> 00:19:51,527
to all the people in our country.

182
00:20:19,502 --> 00:20:21,784
to all the peoples of Europe.

183
00:20:51,650 --> 00:20:53,442
to all people on earth.

184
00:21:22,008 --> 00:21:25,757
And finally, to all beings in all directions.

